{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"My talk is \"Flapping Birds and Space Telescopes.\""},{"time":3000,"text":"And you would think that should have nothing to do with one another,"},{"time":5000,"text":"but I hope by the end of these 18 minutes,"},{"time":8000,"text":"you'll see a little bit of a relation."},{"time":11000,"text":"It ties to origami. So let me start."},{"time":12000,"text":"What is origami?"},{"time":14000,"text":"Most people think they know what origami is. It's this:"},{"time":17000,"text":"flapping birds, toys, cootie catchers, that sort of thing."},{"time":20000,"text":"And that is what origami used to be."},{"time":22000,"text":"But it's become something else."},{"time":24000,"text":"It's become an art form, a form of sculpture."}]},{"cues":[{"time":26000,"text":"The common theme -- what makes it origami --"},{"time":28000,"text":"is folding is how we create the form."},{"time":32000,"text":"You know, it's very old. This is a plate from 1797."},{"time":35000,"text":"It shows these women playing with these toys."},{"time":37000,"text":"If you look close, it's this shape, called a crane."},{"time":40000,"text":"Every Japanese kid"},{"time":42000,"text":"learns how to fold that crane."},{"time":44000,"text":"So this art has been around for hundreds of years,"},{"time":46000,"text":"and you would think something"},{"time":48000,"text":"that's been around that long -- so restrictive, folding only --"},{"time":51000,"text":"everything that could be done has been done a long time ago."},{"time":54000,"text":"And that might have been the case."}]},{"cues":[{"time":56000,"text":"But in the twentieth century,"},{"time":58000,"text":"a Japanese folder named Yoshizawa came along,"},{"time":61000,"text":"and he created tens of thousands of new designs."},{"time":64000,"text":"But even more importantly, he created a language,"},{"time":67000,"text":"a way we could communicate,"},{"time":69000,"text":"a code of dots, dashes and arrows."},{"time":71000,"text":"Harkening back to Susan Blackmore's talk,"},{"time":73000,"text":"we now have a means of transmitting information"},{"time":75000,"text":"with heredity and selection,"},{"time":78000,"text":"and we know where that leads."},{"time":80000,"text":"And where it has led in origami"},{"time":82000,"text":"is to things like this."},{"time":84000,"text":"This is an origami figure --"},{"time":86000,"text":"one sheet, no cuts, folding only, hundreds of folds."},{"time":92000,"text":"This, too, is origami,"},{"time":94000,"text":"and this shows where we've gone in the modern world."},{"time":97000,"text":"Naturalism. Detail."},{"time":99000,"text":"You can get horns, antlers --"},{"time":101000,"text":"even, if you look close, cloven hooves."}]},{"cues":[{"time":103000,"text":"And it raises a question: what changed?"},{"time":106000,"text":"And what changed is something"},{"time":108000,"text":"you might not have expected in an art,"},{"time":111000,"text":"which is math."},{"time":113000,"text":"That is, people applied mathematical principles"},{"time":115000,"text":"to the art,"},{"time":118000,"text":"to discover the underlying laws."},{"time":120000,"text":"And that leads to a very powerful tool."},{"time":123000,"text":"The secret to productivity in so many fields --"},{"time":125000,"text":"and in origami --"},{"time":127000,"text":"is letting dead people do your work for you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":130000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":131000,"text":"Because what you can do is"},{"time":133000,"text":"take your problem,"},{"time":135000,"text":"and turn it into a problem that someone else has solved,"},{"time":138000,"text":"and use their solutions."},{"time":140000,"text":"And I want to tell you how we did that in origami."},{"time":143000,"text":"Origami revolves around crease patterns."},{"time":145000,"text":"The crease pattern shown here is the underlying blueprint"},{"time":148000,"text":"for an origami figure."},{"time":150000,"text":"And you can't just draw them arbitrarily."},{"time":152000,"text":"They have to obey four simple laws."},{"time":155000,"text":"And they're very simple, easy to understand."},{"time":157000,"text":"The first law is two-colorability. You can color any crease pattern"},{"time":160000,"text":"with just two colors without ever having"},{"time":162000,"text":"the same color meeting."},{"time":165000,"text":"The directions of the folds at any vertex --"},{"time":168000,"text":"the number of mountain folds, the number of valley folds --"},{"time":171000,"text":"always differs by two. Two more or two less."},{"time":173000,"text":"Nothing else."},{"time":175000,"text":"If you look at the angles around the fold,"},{"time":177000,"text":"you find that if you number the angles in a circle,"},{"time":179000,"text":"all the even-numbered angles add up to a straight line,"},{"time":182000,"text":"all the odd-numbered angles add up to a straight line."},{"time":185000,"text":"And if you look at how the layers stack,"},{"time":187000,"text":"you'll find that no matter how you stack folds and sheets,"},{"time":190000,"text":"a sheet can never"},{"time":192000,"text":"penetrate a fold."},{"time":194000,"text":"So that's four simple laws. That's all you need in origami."},{"time":197000,"text":"All of origami comes from that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":199000,"text":"And you'd think, \"Can four simple laws"},{"time":201000,"text":"give rise to that kind of complexity?\""},{"time":203000,"text":"But indeed, the laws of quantum mechanics"},{"time":205000,"text":"can be written down on a napkin,"},{"time":207000,"text":"and yet they govern all of chemistry,"},{"time":209000,"text":"all of life, all of history."},{"time":211000,"text":"If we obey these laws,"},{"time":213000,"text":"we can do amazing things."},{"time":215000,"text":"So in origami, to obey these laws,"},{"time":217000,"text":"we can take simple patterns --"},{"time":219000,"text":"like this repeating pattern of folds, called textures --"},{"time":222000,"text":"and by itself it's nothing."},{"time":224000,"text":"But if we follow the laws of origami,"},{"time":226000,"text":"we can put these patterns into another fold"},{"time":229000,"text":"that itself might be something very, very simple,"},{"time":231000,"text":"but when we put it together,"},{"time":233000,"text":"we get something a little different."},{"time":235000,"text":"This fish, 400 scales --"},{"time":238000,"text":"again, it is one uncut square, only folding."},{"time":242000,"text":"And if you don't want to fold 400 scales,"},{"time":244000,"text":"you can back off and just do a few things,"},{"time":246000,"text":"and add plates to the back of a turtle, or toes."},{"time":249000,"text":"Or you can ramp up and go up to 50 stars"},{"time":252000,"text":"on a flag, with 13 stripes."},{"time":255000,"text":"And if you want to go really crazy,"},{"time":258000,"text":"1,000 scales on a rattlesnake."},{"time":260000,"text":"And this guy's on display downstairs,"},{"time":262000,"text":"so take a look if you get a chance."}]},{"cues":[{"time":265000,"text":"The most powerful tools in origami"},{"time":267000,"text":"have related to how we get parts of creatures."},{"time":270000,"text":"And I can put it in this simple equation."},{"time":272000,"text":"We take an idea,"},{"time":274000,"text":"combine it with a square, and you get an origami figure."}]},{"cues":[{"time":277000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":281000,"text":"What matters is what we mean by those symbols."},{"time":283000,"text":"And you might say, \"Can you really be that specific?"},{"time":286000,"text":"I mean, a stag beetle -- it's got two points for jaws,"},{"time":288000,"text":"it's got antennae. Can you be that specific in the detail?\""},{"time":292000,"text":"And yeah, you really can."},{"time":295000,"text":"So how do we do that? Well, we break it down"},{"time":298000,"text":"into a few smaller steps."},{"time":300000,"text":"So let me stretch out that equation."},{"time":302000,"text":"I start with my idea. I abstract it."},{"time":305000,"text":"What's the most abstract form? It's a stick figure."},{"time":308000,"text":"And from that stick figure, I somehow have to get to a folded shape"},{"time":311000,"text":"that has a part for every bit of the subject,"},{"time":314000,"text":"a flap for every leg."},{"time":316000,"text":"And then once I have that folded shape that we call the base,"},{"time":319000,"text":"you can make the legs narrower, you can bend them,"},{"time":322000,"text":"you can turn it into the finished shape."}]},{"cues":[{"time":324000,"text":"Now the first step, pretty easy."},{"time":326000,"text":"Take an idea, draw a stick figure."},{"time":328000,"text":"The last step is not so hard, but that middle step --"},{"time":331000,"text":"going from the abstract description to the folded shape --"},{"time":334000,"text":"that's hard."},{"time":336000,"text":"But that's the place where the mathematical ideas"},{"time":338000,"text":"can get us over the hump."},{"time":340000,"text":"And I'm going to show you all how to do that"},{"time":342000,"text":"so you can go out of here and fold something."},{"time":344000,"text":"But we're going to start small."},{"time":346000,"text":"This base has a lot of flaps in it."},{"time":348000,"text":"We're going to learn how to make one flap."},{"time":351000,"text":"How would you make a single flap?"},{"time":353000,"text":"Take a square. Fold it in half, fold it in half, fold it again,"},{"time":356000,"text":"until it gets long and narrow,"},{"time":358000,"text":"and then we'll say at the end of that, that's a flap."},{"time":360000,"text":"I could use that for a leg, an arm, anything like that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":363000,"text":"What paper went into that flap?"},{"time":365000,"text":"Well, if I unfold it and go back to the crease pattern,"},{"time":367000,"text":"you can see that the upper left corner of that shape"},{"time":370000,"text":"is the paper that went into the flap."},{"time":372000,"text":"So that's the flap, and all the rest of the paper's left over."},{"time":375000,"text":"I can use it for something else."},{"time":377000,"text":"Well, there are other ways of making a flap."},{"time":379000,"text":"There are other dimensions for flaps."},{"time":381000,"text":"If I make the flaps skinnier, I can use a bit less paper."},{"time":384000,"text":"If I make the flap as skinny as possible,"},{"time":387000,"text":"I get to the limit of the minimum amount of paper needed."},{"time":390000,"text":"And you can see there, it needs a quarter-circle of paper to make a flap."},{"time":394000,"text":"There's other ways of making flaps."},{"time":396000,"text":"If I put the flap on the edge, it uses a half circle of paper."},{"time":399000,"text":"And if I make the flap from the middle, it uses a full circle."},{"time":402000,"text":"So, no matter how I make a flap,"},{"time":404000,"text":"it needs some part"},{"time":406000,"text":"of a circular region of paper."},{"time":408000,"text":"So now we're ready to scale up."},{"time":410000,"text":"What if I want to make something that has a lot of flaps?"},{"time":413000,"text":"What do I need? I need a lot of circles."}]},{"cues":[{"time":417000,"text":"And in the 1990s,"},{"time":419000,"text":"origami artists discovered these principles"},{"time":421000,"text":"and realized we could make arbitrarily complicated figures"},{"time":424000,"text":"just by packing circles."},{"time":427000,"text":"And here's where the dead people start to help us out,"},{"time":430000,"text":"because lots of people have studied"},{"time":433000,"text":"the problem of packing circles."},{"time":435000,"text":"I can rely on that vast history of mathematicians and artists"},{"time":438000,"text":"looking at disc packings and arrangements."},{"time":441000,"text":"And I can use those patterns now to create origami shapes."},{"time":445000,"text":"So we figured out these rules whereby you pack circles,"},{"time":447000,"text":"you decorate the patterns of circles with lines"},{"time":450000,"text":"according to more rules. That gives you the folds."},{"time":452000,"text":"Those folds fold into a base. You shape the base."},{"time":455000,"text":"You get a folded shape -- in this case, a cockroach."},{"time":459000,"text":"And it's so simple."}]},{"cues":[{"time":461000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":464000,"text":"It's so simple that a computer could do it."},{"time":467000,"text":"And you say, \"Well, you know, how simple is that?\""},{"time":469000,"text":"But computers -- you need to be able to describe things"},{"time":471000,"text":"in very basic terms, and with this, we could."},{"time":474000,"text":"So I wrote a computer program a bunch of years ago"},{"time":476000,"text":"called TreeMaker, and you can download it from my website."},{"time":478000,"text":"It's free. It runs on all the major platforms -- even Windows."}]},{"cues":[{"time":481000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":483000,"text":"And you just draw a stick figure,"},{"time":485000,"text":"and it calculates the crease pattern."},{"time":487000,"text":"It does the circle packing, calculates the crease pattern,"},{"time":490000,"text":"and if you use that stick figure that I just showed --"},{"time":492000,"text":"which you can kind of tell, it's a deer, it's got antlers --"},{"time":495000,"text":"you'll get this crease pattern."},{"time":497000,"text":"And if you take this crease pattern, you fold on the dotted lines,"},{"time":499000,"text":"you'll get a base that you can then shape"},{"time":502000,"text":"into a deer,"},{"time":504000,"text":"with exactly the crease pattern that you wanted."},{"time":506000,"text":"And if you want a different deer,"},{"time":508000,"text":"not a white-tailed deer, but you want a mule deer, or an elk,"},{"time":511000,"text":"you change the packing,"},{"time":513000,"text":"and you can do an elk."},{"time":515000,"text":"Or you could do a moose."},{"time":517000,"text":"Or, really, any other kind of deer."},{"time":519000,"text":"These techniques revolutionized this art."},{"time":522000,"text":"We found we could do insects,"},{"time":524000,"text":"spiders, which are close,"},{"time":526000,"text":"things with legs, things with legs and wings,"},{"time":530000,"text":"things with legs and antennae."},{"time":532000,"text":"And if folding a single praying mantis from a single uncut square"},{"time":535000,"text":"wasn't interesting enough,"},{"time":537000,"text":"then you could do two praying mantises"},{"time":539000,"text":"from a single uncut square."},{"time":541000,"text":"She's eating him."},{"time":543000,"text":"I call it \"Snack Time.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":546000,"text":"And you can do more than just insects."},{"time":548000,"text":"This -- you can put details,"},{"time":550000,"text":"toes and claws. A grizzly bear has claws."},{"time":553000,"text":"This tree frog has toes."},{"time":555000,"text":"Actually, lots of people in origami now put toes into their models."},{"time":558000,"text":"Toes have become an origami meme,"},{"time":560000,"text":"because everyone's doing it."},{"time":563000,"text":"You can make multiple subjects."},{"time":565000,"text":"So these are a couple of instrumentalists."},{"time":567000,"text":"The guitar player from a single square,"},{"time":570000,"text":"the bass player from a single square."},{"time":572000,"text":"And if you say, \"Well, but the guitar, bass --"},{"time":574000,"text":"that's not so hot."},{"time":576000,"text":"Do a little more complicated instrument.\""},{"time":578000,"text":"Well, then you could do an organ."}]},{"cues":[{"time":580000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":583000,"text":"And what this has allowed is the creation"},{"time":585000,"text":"of origami-on-demand."},{"time":587000,"text":"So now people can say, \"I want exactly this and this and this,\""},{"time":590000,"text":"and you can go out and fold it."},{"time":593000,"text":"And sometimes you create high art,"},{"time":595000,"text":"and sometimes you pay the bills by doing some commercial work."},{"time":598000,"text":"But I want to show you some examples."},{"time":600000,"text":"Everything you'll see here,"},{"time":602000,"text":"except the car, is origami."}]},{"cues":[{"time":605000,"text":"(Video)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":633000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":636000,"text":"Just to show you, this really was folded paper."},{"time":639000,"text":"Computers made things move,"},{"time":641000,"text":"but these were all real, folded objects that we made."},{"time":645000,"text":"And we can use this not just for visuals,"},{"time":648000,"text":"but it turns out to be useful even in the real world."},{"time":651000,"text":"Surprisingly, origami"},{"time":652000,"text":"and the structures that we've developed in origami"},{"time":655000,"text":"turn out to have applications in medicine, in science,"},{"time":658000,"text":"in space, in the body, consumer electronics and more."}]},{"cues":[{"time":661000,"text":"And I want to show you some of these examples."},{"time":664000,"text":"One of the earliest was this pattern,"},{"time":666000,"text":"this folded pattern,"},{"time":668000,"text":"studied by Koryo Miura, a Japanese engineer."},{"time":671000,"text":"He studied a folding pattern, and realized"},{"time":673000,"text":"this could fold down into an extremely compact package"},{"time":676000,"text":"that had a very simple opening and closing structure."},{"time":679000,"text":"And he used it to design this solar array."},{"time":682000,"text":"It's an artist's rendition, but it flew in a Japanese telescope"},{"time":685000,"text":"in 1995."},{"time":687000,"text":"Now, there is actually a little origami"},{"time":689000,"text":"in the James Webb Space Telescope, but it's very simple."},{"time":692000,"text":"The telescope, going up in space,"},{"time":694000,"text":"it unfolds in two places."},{"time":697000,"text":"It folds in thirds. It's a very simple pattern --"},{"time":699000,"text":"you wouldn't even call that origami."},{"time":701000,"text":"They certainly didn't need to talk to origami artists."}]},{"cues":[{"time":704000,"text":"But if you want to go higher and go larger than this,"},{"time":707000,"text":"then you might need some origami."},{"time":709000,"text":"Engineers at Lawrence Livermore National Lab"},{"time":711000,"text":"had an idea for a telescope much larger."},{"time":714000,"text":"They called it the Eyeglass."},{"time":716000,"text":"The design called for geosynchronous orbit"},{"time":718000,"text":"25,000 miles up,"},{"time":720000,"text":"100-meter diameter lens."},{"time":723000,"text":"So, imagine a lens the size of a football field."},{"time":726000,"text":"There were two groups of people who were interested in this:"},{"time":728000,"text":"planetary scientists, who want to look up,"},{"time":731000,"text":"and then other people, who wanted to look down."},{"time":735000,"text":"Whether you look up or look down,"},{"time":737000,"text":"how do you get it up in space? You've got to get it up there in a rocket."},{"time":740000,"text":"And rockets are small. So you have to make it smaller."},{"time":743000,"text":"How do you make a large sheet of glass smaller?"},{"time":745000,"text":"Well, about the only way is to fold it up somehow."},{"time":748000,"text":"So you have to do something like this."},{"time":750000,"text":"This was a small model."}]},{"cues":[{"time":753000,"text":"Folded lens, you divide up the panels, you add flexures."},{"time":755000,"text":"But this pattern's not going to work"},{"time":758000,"text":"to get something 100 meters down to a few meters."},{"time":761000,"text":"So the Livermore engineers,"},{"time":763000,"text":"wanting to make use of the work of dead people,"},{"time":765000,"text":"or perhaps live origamists, said,"},{"time":768000,"text":"\"Let's see if someone else is doing this sort of thing.\""},{"time":771000,"text":"So they looked into the origami community,"},{"time":774000,"text":"we got in touch with them, and I started working with them."},{"time":776000,"text":"And we developed a pattern together"},{"time":778000,"text":"that scales to arbitrarily large size,"},{"time":780000,"text":"but that allows any flat ring or disc"},{"time":784000,"text":"to fold down into a very neat, compact cylinder."},{"time":787000,"text":"And they adopted that for their first generation,"},{"time":789000,"text":"which was not 100 meters -- it was a five-meter."},{"time":791000,"text":"But this is a five-meter telescope --"},{"time":793000,"text":"has about a quarter-mile focal length."},{"time":795000,"text":"And it works perfectly on its test range,"},{"time":797000,"text":"and it indeed folds up into a neat little bundle."}]},{"cues":[{"time":801000,"text":"Now, there is other origami in space."},{"time":803000,"text":"Japan Aerospace [Exploration] Agency flew a solar sail,"},{"time":806000,"text":"and you can see here that the sail expands out,"},{"time":809000,"text":"and you can still see the fold lines."},{"time":811000,"text":"The problem that's being solved here is"},{"time":814000,"text":"something that needs to be big and sheet-like at its destination,"},{"time":817000,"text":"but needs to be small for the journey."},{"time":819000,"text":"And that works whether you're going into space,"},{"time":822000,"text":"or whether you're just going into a body."},{"time":825000,"text":"And this example is the latter."},{"time":827000,"text":"This is a heart stent developed by Zhong You"},{"time":830000,"text":"at Oxford University."},{"time":832000,"text":"It holds open a blocked artery when it gets to its destination,"},{"time":835000,"text":"but it needs to be much smaller for the trip there,"},{"time":838000,"text":"through your blood vessels."},{"time":840000,"text":"And this stent folds down using an origami pattern,"},{"time":843000,"text":"based on a model called the water bomb base."}]},{"cues":[{"time":847000,"text":"Airbag designers also have the problem"},{"time":849000,"text":"of getting flat sheets"},{"time":851000,"text":"into a small space."},{"time":854000,"text":"And they want to do their design by simulation."},{"time":856000,"text":"So they need to figure out how, in a computer,"},{"time":858000,"text":"to flatten an airbag."},{"time":860000,"text":"And the algorithms that we developed"},{"time":862000,"text":"to do insects"},{"time":864000,"text":"turned out to be the solution for airbags"},{"time":867000,"text":"to do their simulation."},{"time":869000,"text":"And so they can do a simulation like this."},{"time":872000,"text":"Those are the origami creases forming,"},{"time":874000,"text":"and now you can see the airbag inflate"},{"time":876000,"text":"and find out, does it work?"},{"time":879000,"text":"And that leads"},{"time":881000,"text":"to a really interesting idea."}]},{"cues":[{"time":883000,"text":"You know, where did these things come from?"},{"time":886000,"text":"Well, the heart stent"},{"time":888000,"text":"came from that little blow-up box"},{"time":890000,"text":"that you might have learned in elementary school."},{"time":893000,"text":"It's the same pattern, called the water bomb base."},{"time":896000,"text":"The airbag-flattening algorithm"},{"time":898000,"text":"came from all the developments"},{"time":900000,"text":"of circle packing and the mathematical theory"},{"time":903000,"text":"that was really developed"},{"time":905000,"text":"just to create insects -- things with legs."},{"time":909000,"text":"The thing is, that this often happens"},{"time":911000,"text":"in math and science."},{"time":913000,"text":"When you get math involved, problems that you solve"},{"time":916000,"text":"for aesthetic value only,"},{"time":918000,"text":"or to create something beautiful,"},{"time":920000,"text":"turn around and turn out"},{"time":922000,"text":"to have an application in the real world."},{"time":925000,"text":"And as weird and surprising as it may sound,"},{"time":928000,"text":"origami may someday even save a life."},{"time":932000,"text":"Thanks."}]},{"cues":[{"time":934000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}